    "overall_strategy": "The synthesis network begins in hydrothermal environments with reduction of CO2 to pyruvate and formation of HCN from CO and NH3, providing key carbon and nitrogen inputs. Surface environments utilize wet-dry cycles and UV photocatalysis on mineral surfaces to assemble imidazole via two convergent routes (formose-derived glyoxal pathway and HCN oligomerization) and form imidazoleacetaldehyde through condensation with glycolaldehyde. Pyruvate flows from hydrothermal to surface for coupling with imidazole to form imidazolepyruvate. The biochemical stage completes assembly via Strecker synthesis and hydrolysis to histidine, or transamination with alanine (derived from pyruvate) to interconvert and produce histidine, ensuring multiple redundant pathways with environmental interconnections.",
